caption: This place's noodles are to die for! Best lamb skewers I've had in the states. Everything I ordered made me nostalgic.
Stunning xi'an food. Excellent flavors. Excellent service.

This Xi'an food is incredibly great with super good prices and tastes. Every time I travel to Chicago, I always remember to go there. As a Chinese, I always respect broad Chinese food culture. Xi'an is the capital of Shaanxi Province, which is famous for noodles and cooked wheaten food. I have tried  Roujiamo Chinese Hamburger, Paomo Mutton and Bread Pieces in Soup there. These are amazing! Even though I am not originally from Xi'an, the taste in this restaurant is the same as what I had back in Beijing, China. It is hard to tell how much I like this restaurant! It is one of my favorites in Chicago and I highly recommend everyone who sees this review to go there!

We also loved the boba (quality original milk tea with tapioca, and my friend loved the peach milk tea with popping boba). Definitely check this place out!

This is a unique restaurant in Chinatown that serves food from Shaanxi province. The place is very vegetarian friendly and all the items are marked. The cold appetizers, called Chinese tapas here, are unique. But the standout is the filled pancake. Like a Chinese version of Gorditas. The handpulled noodles are toothsome, tasty and filling. The spicing is more vinegar based than soy sauce. They also have chili oil on hand. All in all I think this is a great opportunity for us to try regional food that's not available widely.
This place gives amazing service as well as tasty menu. My favourite spot around town. The drinks and food served fast and the prices were fair. Highly recommended.

Probably my favorite spot in Chinatown. The cumin lamb flatbread sandwich is delicious. The handpulled noodles with lamb is also fantastic. The soups are decent, but I'd stick with the noodles and flatbread sandwiches.  The service is generally good. I get seated very quickly, served with really wonderful green tea (very fragrant, almost like drinking a light perfume), and the food comes out pretty fast.  The reason I'm only giving this a 4 is because I wish the flavors were more robust, and the lamb more gamy - it is always mild, with a slight lamb flavor, but I prefer it when it's stronger, like when I go to the Persian places. Though that's a matter of preference. It's a 4.5 for the food.  I'm satisfied giving a 4 out of 5, however, since there's an extra charge to use a credit card for orders under 20 bucks. I have been given the wrong item a couple of times and charged more for it. Though that's a small gripe and nothing I ever bothered complaining about since I enjoyed it anyway.

Great hand pulled noodles! Number 60 is a delicious noodle with meat, eggs, and a spicy sauce. The marinated tofu #3 is ok. The lamb skewer #72 is juicy and flavorful. The best thing was the beef flat bread #25, the bread crispy and the beef flavorful. Credit accepted, metered street parking, come for the noodles and flat bread

I couldn’t tolerant their service even as a patient loyal customer. We visit this place every time when we have a trip to Chicago. The service is kind of slow but okay for us because of the delicious food. However this time, called 20min before for a takeout order, and waited another 20 min because when I arrived part of the order has not even been started yet. I feel the declining in their service, and I hope the bad service won’t spoil  my enjoyment for the food.

Flatbreads are delicious and fresh but the noodles were very lackluster. We got the hot and sour hand pulled noodles and the sauce was just oily and bland. The chili oil at the table was also bland and tasted very stale. Would only come back here for the flatbreads.

I was not satisfied with the service so I gave A small tip. And you know what, when i returned home and check out the transaction record on my credit card, they TAMPERED my tip amount! Everybody be careful. I will not call the police this time. But this is truly illegal! No comment on the food does not mean i think you deserve  Xian's title.

This is one of the restaurants that I most regularly and frequently visit in Chicago. Everything on the menu is extremely good, and the prices are very cheap. The portions are more than enough.  My go-tos are the hot and sour noodles, noodles in lamb soup, and cumin lamb flatbread. The grilled meat skewers are great as well but I usually pass on them because the noodle dishes come with meat. The noodles are definitely the main attraction here and are always perfectly wide and chewy. Above all else, avoid the bubble teas here. Just stick with the food.  Xi'an Cuisine is almost always very busy, which means that sometimes they'll sit you at a communal/shared table. The restaurant itself is not always the cleanest and service has been hit or miss for me, but I'll keep coming back because the value is simply unbeatable.

This place is THE BOMB! I grew up in the SF Bay Area and have eaten a lot of good Chinese food, but this place totally rocks! I got the cumin lamb flatbread sandwich and the hand-pulled noodles in hot and sour sauce. The noodles were pretty good, but that cumin lamb sandwich was to die for. The place was almost full at 3:30 PM on a weekday, and I was the only non-Asian there. There was a language barrier with me and the waitress, but she was still cordial and suggested the noodle dish I got. The chef (and I think owner) was AWESOME! As I was eating, I noticed he was standing in the order window watching me and smiling. When he saw that I noticed that, he didn't duck away or anything creepy, instead he waved with his big smile. I gave him 2 thumbs up, and he gave me 2 thumbs up back! Then he went to have a smoke out front but stopped at my table to ask how the meal was. I told him "GREAT!" and he thanked me, then went out front to smoke. This was about last November I think. This is a must go for my every time I visit Chicago from here on out!

We love the food from the famous Xi An restaurant in New York, so we always compare what we had here with what we tried in NY. We really like Xi An food. I used to not like eating lamb, but because of Xi An food, I came to love lamb dishes. So, if you like lamb and spicy, please give Xi An food a try. Anyway, we ordered Liang Bi. I had to say it was not flavorful at all, very plain. The only dish I enjoyed was the Biang Biang noodles. My son and husband enjoy the lamb burger. But, if you have tried it at the famous Xi An restaurant in NY and hoping Chicago has the same one, you’ll be disappointed.

This is easily the best restaurant in Chinatown, and arguably Chicago. It is authentic Xi’an cuisine, and it is delicious. The meat is tender and well seasoned, and the noodles are handmade, soft, and absolutely BEAUTIFULLY flavored. And the staff are very nice, which is just the cherry on top! I recommend the Flatbreads, and Liang Pi cold noodles. The Biang Biang Mien is also just brilliant. Easiest 5 star I’ve ever given in my life.

I went here last time I was in Chicago, about 6 months ago. I had planned on making it here in previous trips, but it never happened. Wish I hadn't made that mistake! So I walked in around 3:30 PM on a week day and the place was about 75% full. All people but me were Asian. Very good signs! Got the noodles in hot and sour sauce without any meat, plus a cumin lamb flatbread sandwich. Noodles were very good and plentiful, but wish I had gotten beef or lamb addition for 2 bucks more to give it a little more flavor. The cumin lamb sandwich was off the hook! I couldn't finish the noodles but was able to eat a little more than half of them, along with the sandwich. Chef/owner was very friendly, waved to me while I was eating and I gave him 2 thumbs up. He gave me 2 thumbs back! He also went out to smoke and stopped for a second to thank me for coming in. An absolute required stop anytime I am in Chicago!

Xi'an was great. When we arrived there was no wait. It is a very small and crowded restaurant. Initially, they seated us at a table for four. (There were two of us.) But, before we ordered they said they needed to move us so they could seat a group of four. We were moved to share a table for six with two couples. That added to the experience.  They make the food to order so it doesn't all come out at once. This added to the experience. We had their Thin potato slices in sour & spicy sauce as an appetizer - this was kind of a potato slaw, quite spicy and a little crisp. Very nice.  For our meals, we share two items: (1) Biang biang noodles with beef and (2) Cumin Hand-stretched noodle soup with lamb. Both were excellent. The Biang biang noodles were chewy with a vinegar flavor. There was a light cumin flavor to the other dish. The meat in the Biang Biang was fairly plentiful, both chucks as well as mince. The lamb was flavorful, in small slices.  The other meals at our table, not sure what they were, but they looked really good. The grass is always greener.  Next time I'm in that area, I will go back to try other items.

I'm a sucker for Xi'an style food and this spot is the best (and also possibly the only) place in chinatown for it. Everytime I come in here I am the only person who is "white" which I take as a good sign since it's authentic. Xi'an is a chinese province and it is on the far western side of China so it's close to the middle east and that type of flavor gets mixed into chinese cuisine and it creates an amazing culinary child. There is a lot of cumin and lamb mixed into chinese things you are used to. I highly recommend their lamb pita which is a small flatbread that is like pita filled with lamb. It's three dollars and it's the best three dollars you'll ever spend. I also recommend the hand pulled noodles in the soy sauce and vinegar. You can get it for $6 if you don't include a protein and to be honest you don't need one, it's so tasty on its own. The noodles aren't hand pulled like you're used to, they are like a small dough ball that's pulled apart flat by the thumbs so it's a wide flat uneven noodle that picks up a lot of sauce and flavor.
Not that authentic but above expected in the US. 肉夹馍 was a surprise.

It's pretty good for the price you pay. I really enjoy the cold noodles and the pork stew burger.  I love that we have northern Chinese cuisine here in Chicago. Xian has dishes that are influenced by the middle east that goes all the way back to the Silk Road days. Therefore, you'll find lamb, cumin spices, and spice powders that are fused with Chinese cuisine. It's pretty unique from all the Westernized Chinese meals I've had.  Protip: go for the pork burger. Also, if you order a side of meat, they give you plenty of it for $6-7.
